comment: This is so hard to listen to because it mirrors my experiences in many ways. Especially hearing her say that judges and juries won't believe him. But I didn't have the benefit of being rich and famous, of being able to afford expensive lawyers, or having the criminal justice system give me preferential treatment the way famous people do. I'm a man that endured long term physical, emotional, and psychological abuse, as well as being manipulated into keeping quiet through constant gaslighting, lies and exploitation of gender bias. There were times when I was so broken and confused that I actually started to believe I deserved it. I lived constantly under threat of being arrested for things I didn't do, while enduring the exact crimes that would be claimed against me if I asked for help. And my fear was justified. She finally followed through on all the threats, she lied, I was arrested, and the police didn't even try to listen. The courts didn't listen or care. They ASSUMED she was telling the truth, despite evidence, even video I tried to present. I spent weeks in jail, months in mental health wards, I have PTSD, and I was suicidal and deeply depressed for a long time after because it was unbearable to have everyone treat you like a monster when you were the victim. I didn't see my daughter for seven months. I was homeless. And I was almost kicked out of the military. All because she was able to get away with lying and have everyone blindly trust her. The crazy thing is, I had volunteered as a sexual assault victim advocate for nearly 10 years when it finally all went to hell. They won't let me volunteer anymore though, even after the truth has come out and been proven. I've been able to mostly clear my name and move on, but there were zero consequences for her. None. But I'm still an allie and advocate for victims of abuse. I don't blame or hate woman. I still consider myself a feminist. But I also work to shed light on the need for men's rights in these situations too. You can't BLINDLY trust anyone who makes an accusation, no matter what their sex or gender. Even now, Amber Heard is being defended by people. She lied and exaggerated and tried to ruin a man's life, and she is still being allowed to go around playing the victim and making money off of it. Woman are abusers in nearly equal numbers to men. The abuse just takes different forms. Stop treating abuse like a sex or gender issue. Men being  physically stronger on average means nothing if they have no power to be believed or trusted.

comment: What people need to understand in domestic abuse cases is that it’s not about gender or feminism or #metoo movement or whatever else, it’s about common sense first and foremost. I’m a feminist and I initially felt like I should be on her side - because that’s a normal human reaction for me, because women get abused so much more than men and I always feel like supporting women who speak up, even if the alleged abuser is one of my most favorite actors ever. However, I didn’t let my beliefs blind me and I never wanted to “cancel” Johnny right away. As we can see, this is never a right move. Regardless, neither was blaming her for false accusations right away back to when it was completely unclear who did what. People need to take a chill pill and realize that it’s necessary to judge everything objectively, and please don’t let this case cloud your future judgements about other abuse allegations from other women.

comment:
I think we need to let the courts figure out what the heck is going on between Depp and Heard. If they're both abusing one another, they need to both have mandatory therapy. If Heard made up her abuse claim so that she could get revenge on Depp for wanting to leave her (or whatever Depp is claiming), then I hope she gets sentenced to community service, has to pay him the 50 million or whatever, and has to get therapy (and vice versa if it turns out he's the one lying). 


This whole thing is incredibly sad -- it's definitely true that women who fight back against their abusers often get labeled abusive themselves, even though their actions were in self-defense, or else are part of a more nuanced situation. I have to say, though, that that voice message didn't sound at all to me as if the situation were mutual in terms of abuse -- if he also hit her, why wouldn't she bring that up when he said he would have to leave if things got physical? Also, how is that recording from 2015 and it's just being released now? What is going onnnnnn???


In any case, to make up claims like this, if there is no truth to them, is vile. This not only effects Depp, but also our entire society -- and obviously makes it more difficult for victims of real abuse to come forward. What really angers me is that no matter what is going on here, at least one of them is trying to take advantage of power over the other, and making us all pawns in that. At least one of them is lying -- maybe both. 


Just a really sad, desperate situation. And I grew up watching Depp and he was always one of my favorite actors -- which is besides the point, but I guess watching all this go down feels a bit like watching insane extended family drama unfold.


Thoughts and prayers go out to whichever one of them is lying the least amount, I guess. And I hope they both get therapy and lots of it. 


Would be super cool if people could learn healthy coping mechanisms BEFORE they enter into romantic partnerships . . . just like a thought. JFC

comment:
The simple fact here is Amber was the abuser, and she was able to game the system to further abuse Johnny Depp.

Abuse isn't even really the right word here, usually this kind of abuse might result in a false criminal charge or simple social ostracism, which are of course both awful in their own right. However, Depp lost a gig as Jack Sparrow on The Pirates of the Carribean movies... and a lot of other acting prospects. He can't get those back. That's millions of dollars.

And why did he lose those things? It's not because of her, by the way... although I think we would like to think so. It's because of us, collectively. It's because people rushed to judgement, because people demanded extrajudicial penalties without trial or investigation.

Well, we got exactly what we fucking asked for didn't we!?! And how did that work out?

Maybe. Just maybe, we might want to take this as a lesson. You see, in the old days, it's not that people didn't care about domestic violence. It's that, they recognized that they didn't know the situation, so they stayed out of it for fear that in intervening they might actually make it worse, like we all did in this case. Now, was that the ideal way to do it? No. Total inaction is not a good way to handle it either, however, obviously jumping the shark and rushing to judgement is clearly wrong too.

You want to take action, but you also don't want to do harm. The only reasonable course of action to accomplish both is to encourage legal action. That is where it will get investigated. That's where JUSTICE gets done, not this lynch mob bullshit.

comment:
Definitely appreciate your promotion of election reform. The Iowa caucus malfunctions and “quality control” jokes are fun and all, but I think we should use this moment as an opportunity to shine a light on just how problematic our archaic voting systems really are and the benefits behind alternative frameworks. 
Implementing a Ranked-Choice Voting system (RCV) and/or Approval Based Voting system (ABV) with a backup paper ballot solves for the issues we’re seeing here tonight and in this election cycle. RCV promotes the same values as caucusing, in that if your preferred candidate doesn’t meet the threshold of viability your vote is deferred to a secondary candidate and so on. It does this without the strain of corralling people for hours on end, making voting more accessible to the working class who can’t justify leaving the workplace or their homes for several hours to cast their vote. ABV takes the now infamous electability question off of the table. With the ability to cast a vote in favor of whichever candidates you are preferable towards there isn’t this anxiety of making sure your vote goes to The Best Candidate to Beat Donald Trump™, there is never any vote splitting or spoiler candidates, and there is never any doubt that whomever is nominated for the candidacy truly represents and has the approval/support of their party. ABV has the potential to cut through the immense political polarization we see in this country, as it disavows the notion that a voters power can only be meaningful when cast for one of two unrepresentative establishment parties and instead allows the voters to support a number of candidates who truly align with their interests.
Without even mentioning the other systemic inadequacies regarding democratic access (and there are plenty) it’s time we advocate for our representative democracy to function using election systems/frameworks that allow for actual representation to even be feasible. There are plenty of alternative methods to our current practices that can and should be implemented to ensure this, it’s just a matter of if we want it bad enough.

comment: As a women who has been emotionally and physically abused from a very young age, I will always support others, especially women, when they do decide to come forth. People do need to talk about abuse in general and how it does have an effect. But... here's my thing, when Amber Heard started to come out about the accusations of Johnny Depp something in my gut was telling me that all of her accusations are either a lie or very exaggerated. I've been a huge Johnny Depp fan, but I was also a big fan for Amber Heard. To me she was a rising actress to keep an eye on and I was so happy when they got together because she seemed wonderful and just nice. But as a kid to both manipulating parents, one a physical abuser and one a narcissistic who emotionally abused, I knew something seem off. It was very sad to see because no one believed Johnny Depp's side to things because he's the guy so he's automatically the aggressor, but I truly always thought she might have been the true aggressor and that audio provides that. Coming from personal experience I think Amber Heard is a narcissist and she's just really good at hiding it. A lot of people think I'm rude for disregarding or having as little respect for my mom because they only think of their own mom and in meeting my mom you wouldn't even suspect the things she's done to me, because narcissistic people are very good at hiding their bad side. That's all they know and in their mind they will do anything in their power to make everyone else seem like the bad guy. But when people do actually meet that side of my mom they finally understand and apologize for assuming any different. Abuse feels like a nightmare that you can't wake up from, you feel even ashamed of it at times. I've never felt that genuine emotion that comes with the abuse she claimed, so I could never had that connection to her accusations, and that voice recording proves why. I think Amber Heard is a genuinely sick person for using the word "abusive" to cover her own abuse, to try to destroy someone emotionally, physically, and career wise. And yes, I'm assuming all this, but it's from the best educated guess I could give. And for her to claim this makes everyone else's abuse story feel invalidated and like they are not going to be heard because she decided that's what it means to be "abused." As a public figure, she can have that power and it's very messed up and immature that that's how she decided to use her power for her own personal gain, to bully others, and destroy.

For they heard them speak with tongues, and magnify God. Then answered Peter, Can any man forbid water, that these should not be baptized, which have received the Holy Ghost as well as we? And he commanded them to be baptized in the name of the Lord).


***(2): Water is to be understood as a symbol for the Holy Spirit. Thus the phrase cold be translated "born of water, even the Spirit."


***(3): Water is to be understood as a symbol of the Word of God. (Ephesians 5:26)<---That he might sanctify and cleanse it with the washing of water by the word). (1 Peter 1:23)<---Being born again, not of corruptible seed, but of incorruptible, by the word of God, which liveth and abideth for ever).


***(4): Jesus used the phrase "born of water" to refer to physical birth. He then used the contrasting phrase "of the Spirit" to refer to spiritual birth.


***(5): Jesus used the phrase "born of water" to refer to John the Baptist's baptism.


***(6): Jesus used the Old Testament imagery of "water" and "wind" to refer to the work of God from above. (Isaiah 44:3-5)<---For I will pour water upon him that is thirsty, and floods upon the dry ground: I will pour my (spirit) upon thy seed, and my (blessing) upon thine offspring: And they shall spring up as among the grass, as willows by the water courses. One shall say, I am the LORD'S; and another shall call himself by the name of Jacob; and another shall subscribe with his hand unto the LORD, and surname himself by the name of Israel.
(Ezekiel 37:9-10)<---Then said he unto me, Prophesy unto the wind, prophesy, son of man, and say to the wind, Thus saith the Lord GOD; Come from the four winds, O breath, and breathe upon these slain, that they may live. So I prophesied as he commanded me, and the (breath) came (into them), and they lived, and stood up upon their feet, an exceeding great army. (Wind) is an alternate translation of the term (Spirit) in verse 8.


***(1 Peter 3:21)<---The like figure whereunto even baptism doth also now save us (not the putting away of the filth of the flesh, but the answer of a good conscience toward God,) by the resurrection of Jesus Christ:


***(Romans 8:9)<---But ye are not in the flesh, but in the Spirit, if so be that the Spirit of God dwell in you. Now if any man have not the Spirit of Christ, he is none of his.

comment: When Heard said he always responds to her physical attacks by "running away", she is admitting he wasn't attacking her. I thought originally that her grainy photos on a neighbor's phone and the ones the next day where she was out partying with friends were instant makeup bruising with no evidence the next day. The narrative given never added up and all support of her story was the neighbor and her significant other repeating the story they discussed after Depp left the apartment over a few hours before they called the cops.  The "leaked" video where he threw the glass was her phone (like she was using an ancient phone with a camera a decade old quality wise) started with her starting a fight. That was her goal, to enter the room, scream, yell, start a fight, and prove he had a temper. He said something about her starting a fight again that was just sick of the attacks, let her go until she moved a bit closer, turned away from her, threw the glass, and left. It felt like it supported his defense and her lying than her story. That audio, if not doctored, is no different. It didn't day she couldn't be a victim either, but it did not include her ever saying he hit her, just her admitting she hit him and he would leave. She sounds like the typical abuser using her prior to him experience as a victim to get the sympathy of fans to further her career. What better target than a big name with an alcohol problem? As much as victims need to be believed, we, as a people, need to look at what is provided rationally because liars exist too. They use movements to generate an emotional response and then slip in to avoid close detection. comment:
Omg wow that Johnny Depp thing...!!! It makes so much fuckin sense looking back. (Aside: yes, amber’s lawyer is correct and just because she may of admitted to hitting him doesn’t mean he never hit her...nevertheless...).  Abuse is about power which is why 9 out of 10 times you’ll see the accused trying to ‘scream louder than the accusations’ with all kinds of counterattacks and denials. Johnny never did that. He just...quietly, silently disappeared. Yes, that could be a tactic to avoid the spotlight and do damage control but now, hearing that, it was probably because he was fuckin freaking out as welll as hurt badly that someone he loved could be so willing to ruin his life so completely. I think that very fact that this tape was released so much later kinda proves this. I mean, hell, the year of #meetoo is prob the WORST time to say an alleged abuse victim ‘painted on bruises’ so why do it now if not that he’s needed this long to process and heal? I’d like to even think that he really didn’t even want to release the tape and had his career and rep either gotten better or not continued to decline from the lies this woman said about him that maybe he never would of released it and exposed her....but that’s entirely speculative & I’m probably making him out to be a better man than he might be (maybe I’m just too happy to be able to root for him again!).

Normally, I would be very careful in allowing one piece evidence sway me on such a serious issue (and I’d be very out spoken against the general public doing the same) but, as a victim of abuse several times over, there is just something so striking in BOTH of their voices that I’d be lying if I said I didn’t whole heartedly believe him. The way she spoke hurt my stomach and the way he spoke (even tho he was clearly drunk in the one part) hurt my heart. I know he’s facing a hell of a battle but I hope he at least gets a fair trial in the face of the public. NOTHING, absolutely NOTHING, hurts the #metoo movement like a woman who cries wolf about abuse. We ask that every woman is believed and listened to when they come forward and it’s women like Amber who make every legitimate abuse case look like an exaggerated grab for attention. The truth is there ARE plenty of women like Amber...the thing is most of them only pull these crazy stunts as teenagers and usually fess up under true police questioning...but even their cases are remembered by men in the community who keep it in the back of their heads, allowing themselves a reason to doubt the story of every other victim they may read about in the future. “Yea right, that b**** is fuckin lying to get attention and to cover her cheating ass cuz that’s exactly what Lauren What’s-her-name did back in senior year”.  Her and Jussie smolette need to go find a cave somewhere together to live out their lives. I won’t wish them death but i will wish them some dark, moldy, wet future in some cold sunless cave. Like Gollum (who was actually a pretty decent guy)

comment:
Amber Heard was once accused of domestic violence against her photographer girlfriend of the time (2009). The girlfriend was the one that spoke on her behalf and defended her after she was arrested. I find this suspicious because victims of abuse defend their attackers more often than they confess the truth of their abuse. It's also suspicious because van Ree, the photographer, had claimed it was a misunderstanding and then went on to compliment and say how she still admired Amber and they were still close. It sounds like she was trying to fight for their relationship even after if got physically abusive. Not only that, but Johnny Depp was seen on a red carpet, being photographed by people at all angles, with bruises on his face that actually match up with his timeline of events. Amber Heard did not have those bruises until later when she needed people to side with her and the way the footage was staged and how she seemed to be pushing his buttons on purpose to get a reaction said the video was faked. Johnny also does in fact have a missing chunk of finger. 

"I was not hitting you." "I'm sorry it was not a proper slap." "You are such a baby. Grow the **ck up!" "When there's not a physical fight you'd still be admirable right? By running away?" "I can't promise you that I'll be perfect. I can't promise you that I won't get physical again." "I just get so mad I lose it." —Amber Heard 2015 Confessional

That was all Amber Heard. Meanwhile, Johnny sounds like a victim who can't let go of their abuser and wants to stay with them despite everything. She very much took advantage of today's Me Too Movement, lied to real victims of abuse, and played her cards to seem more sympathetic. She did so get ahead of the story and even then people were calling her out on her bullshit.

comment:
I am 21 years old and I have been a victim of physical and emotional abuse from a woman.
The worst part is no matter what you do as a man you will always be seen as the aggressor.
Within the last 6 months I have been verbally and physically attacked.
She would often throw things at me and say "I throw things because I can't hit you" which always concerned me.
Recently an argument got so heated I asked her to leave my apartment and she refused. I asked her nicely and I asked her meanly. Nothing worked. As a man I am powerless because as soon as I put my hands on her, I am the bad guy. I am at fault. I told her if she didn't leave my apartment I would physically remove her and call the police. Oh boy she didn't like that. When I finally dialled 9-1-1 she flew into a rage. She smacked a collectors helmet off my living room side table so hard it flew across the room, bounced off the wall, and landed back on the other side. As I was on the phone with dispatch our eyes met, and she charged towards me punched my skull several times and even bit me. The woman on dispatch even said "it sounds like the female is assaulting him now." 
She then flipped the entire side table and threw a bar stool and slammed my apartment door shut.
Not 10 minutes later she started calling me and texting me saying she was sorry and half assed bullshit like she never meant for things to get that way. When I told her the police were getting involved she told me, IN CONFIDENCE, that she would press charges against me and win. She also happened to mention that she should have stabbed me instead of biting me.
I was an emotional and physical wreck. I didn't know what to do. My apartment was a mess, I had a slight concussion, and a bleeding bite wound on my back and the only thing I was worried about was getting arrested.
Me, the one who offered to talk things out at my apartment, but when I felt things were getting too heated I asked her to leave.
I have an Alexa in my bedroom (Alexa's are always recording and can be accessed for investigation purposes) so I made it very clear to her that if she even tries to pull anything that I have the recorded evidence of me asking her to leave my property, and on top of that the witness testimony of the officer that arrived and saw the scene, the recorded dispatch call of her assaulting me and the fact I was admitted to the hospital and given antibiotics for 10 days due to a human bite wound.

Men can be victims too. Women can be abusers. Women can be aggressors. Women can also be master manipulators because of the stigma around abuse in relationships. 
This needs to end.

If you look at the evidence, it is clear that Heard, not Depp, is the abuser. 

I’ve been in an actual abusive relationship. I was stalked and violently assaulted by an ex. I know what abuse looks like - and Heard is not a victim of abuse. I have looked into this case, including at the actual court documents, and have signed a petition in favour of Depp. We should not just believe all women - we should believe all victims who are credible. Heard is not credible - there is so much evidence that proves her wrong, and points to her being the actual abuser. Many victims, especially women, do receive vitriol and abuse when they speak out - that is true. That’s something that we need to change about our society and culture. However, Heard hasn’t received vitriol because she is a victim speaking out; she has been on the receiving end of public anger because she is an abuser who has tried to gaslight both her victim, and the public.

Make no mistake - Amber Heard doesn’t care about women. She cares about herself. She is the very reason why so many actual female victims aren’t believed. Her actions have hurt female victims of abuse, because she is someone people will point to in the future when actual victims come out and try to tell their stories. Actual victims will be dismissed because of her cruel actions. What she has done to Johnny, and to perpetuate the general culture of victim-blaming in our society, is unforgivable. I applaud JK Rowling for standing by Depp, and doing what is right. I certainly won’t see any movies that cast Heard. She doesn’t deserve to be rewarded for her actions. She doesn’t deserve to be attacked or threatened by anyone, but she absolutely deserves to be condemned by the public, and remembered as the abuser that she clearly is.

Yes, men are far more likely than women to be domestic abusers. However, women can still be abusers, and men can still be victims. Just because something is less common does not mean it doesn’t happen. We shouldn’t support all women, regardless of their actions - we should support all VICTIMS, regardless of their sex. Anything else is sexist, unjust, and unethical.

comment: I've had over a dozen MRI's. My advice is:  1) Don't opt for an open MRI because you're worried about being claustrophobic. Your health provider doesn't get as good as an image as with closed and you may to do it again anyway, 2) Go to a Lowes's and get a set of the blue plastic Christmas tree ear plugs. Ones that you scrunch up are worthless. Don't go into the MRI without ear protection or you will be miserable. 3) Ask, plead, or even beg for them to block/stabilize whatever they're trying to view. I had them put my head into a milk crate with the end cut out and then pile sandbags around my head to keep my head from moving when they MRI'd my neck and brain. Holding still for long passes over a 45 minute to 1-1/2 hour session is a bitch. It's better for them to fix/support what they want to image so you can relax. 4) If you have trouble lying on a flat/hard surface for long periods of time, bring a pillow for your lower back and/or something for under your knees to make it comfortable. Once they start they really can't give you a break. 5) Wear gym shorts with comfortable underwear and a plain (no designs/silkscreen/logo) T-shirt. That way you don't have to go naked in a hospital gown. If you can't tolerate 60 degrees then have a sweatshirt/sweatpants. NO METAL FASTERNERS. 6) Probably don't want to eat/drink anything for a few hours before so you dont need to go in the middle of the scan. 7) Ask if you can bring a CD or a thumb drive of music to listen to. Some places will play your tunes through the intercom for you. 8) If you're worried about freaking out being in a closed space for a long time, ask your doctor to prescribe something to calm you down. 9) Tell the technician not to talk to you unless you're doing something wrong or the building is on fire. With my neck/head blocked, a pillow under my lower back, and my knees raised I would get comfortable and fall asleep. They would have to come in the room and shake an ankle to get me to wake up so they could get me to prep before bringing me back out of the tunnel. DM me if you want more advice.

comment:
So here are some thoughts that I had. I am not super well-read on this Depp/Heard situation, so take my thoughts knowing this.

From what I *have* read, both Depp and Heard have had a somewhat recent history of accusing each other of abuse--well recent in that it's been off-and-on for five years. I don't trust Heard's word that she is the sole victim in this relationship. I do wonder if Depp has done more than minor pushing/self-defense maneuvers.


Depp was accused of abusing substances and assaulting a crew member on set a few years ago. His behavior has also been somewhat erratic. I personally have witnessed relationships/marriages where both partners were volatile and violent and explosive. And often, one was a bit more of each than the other.


Is it possible that both Depp and Heard abused each other? If Depp had fallen off the wagon, it could have made him uncharacteristically volatile and reactionary. He also could have been recording that audio intentionally, after provoking her into acting out violently and then talking sweetly while getting a "confession" (this is purely speculation).

This is just the perspective of someone who grew up around this, so I could be reading into crap that isn't there. But it's food for thought.

The sad fact is that we have a culture here where people can simply be accused of something and everyone in a legal position (police, lawyers, judges, etc.) will side with and rule in the accusors' favor, regardless of what the evidence actually shows. This includes issuing restraining orders, which will impact employment opportunities and other things. I think we need to change the way media reports stories like this and the level of publicity and extreme responses to accusations before convictions are made.

I agree, no man/woman should abuse physically, mentally or verbally another person, and much less then lie and bring up false accusations. 
My question is, who was recording the conversation? If it was Depp, then he knew to be careful about what he said, and if Amber knew about it, why incriminate herself? comment:
I dated a girl who behaved the same way as Amber Heard.  I was villainized despite being slapped, headbutted and threatened to be a witness while she self-abused in front of me (none of which I would allow to happen but it is difficult to know what to do in those situations) not to mention the emotional abuse and manipulation which I will not go into detail about here.  Like Depp, I repeatedly said, "I don't want you out of my life.  I am in love with you."  And of course meant it in the deepest way.  During the course of a few weeks I noticed the warmth disappear from the hallways around me and in a painfully slow and confusing manner a cold distance instead take its place.  Friends stopped calling, stopped listening, except a really great few.  Little did I know that in the midst of my frightened desperation this person was taking my story and turning it into her own.  I still have never hurt so bad as I did those years.


I am relieved to know that Johnny Depp's truth is going to make it out since it's very easy to see a pretty female and want to believe her instead of the male.  Trust me, I get that inclination totally and still can't bring myself to resent it.  We never do want to imagine pretty girls as hideous nightmares.  I live vicariously through your vindication, Johnny, since I never did get mine.  I hope you find a gentle, loving lass and live out your days in merriment with her.

People cancelled one of the most beloved actors of our time, someone who largely showed to be a great and kind person in public. They had no problem dropping him. I could give less than two shits what movies these people are in, have a sense of nuance and stop flipping the switch of your outrage based on whoevers story you blindly believe at the moment. comment: As an Iowan I don't know why you find our caucus's confusing, your explanation seemed perfectly concise and comprehensible. I participated in my first caucus in 2016 and it is a very Iowan and entertaining affair. This year they've rearranged Washington township so we've been moved to the new middle schools gym. The best part of the caucus is that it's a head count. There were roughly 150 democrats that showed up in 2016 from my district, a slightly larger number of republicans sat on the other side of the gymnasium conducting their own slightly less chaotic primary. Trying to keep track of all those grumpy old farmers on our side of town during voting is impossible. With out fail every count must be done twice because someone's in the bathroom and the numbers don't add up. I sat with the O'Malley group but we only had half a dozen people. After the first count they give you a break to regroup and we got to argue with the local Hillary representative before sitting with Bernie. That next count took forever because some people had decided to leave but hadn't told the man with the clipboard so the numbers were off. In my district Bernie won by only a few people and we elected a delegate to represent us at the county dnc for Bernie. The whole thing took just over an hour and a half and there was  a bake sale on the way out.
author: WonderfulWin

comment: It's hard to say my thoughts on a story I don't really know as a whole. I do know, and can speak from experience, that her statement was very typical of an abuser. "I didn't punch you, I hit you..." that is not only physical abuse, but mental and emotional abuse. Down playing someone's emotion is a game narcissists play, and I have experienced that first hand. I stayed in an abusive relationship because I thought I was the one with the problem. I remember actually thinking to myself, "well, if I hadn't yelled at him, he wouldn't have hit me. I deserved it." Now, I'm no saint in that regard, either. I tried to force him to stay and talk to me, and got physical with him as well. I would grab him, I would push him, and I would also hit him. It wasn't until I got help that I realized that I wasn't just the victim, but also a perpetrator. Who's to say that he isn't guilty to a degree, either? I think this situation isn't for anyone to judge until we see all sides of the story. I am a huge fan of Depp, but I know everyone is human. I hope he isn't what she claims him to be, but I cannot say that he is entirely innocent, either because I lack the knowledge of thier intimate life. It's hard to recognize your own fault when you've been beaten down physically, emotionally, and mentally. I'm glad I was able to see my own faults and hold myself accountable. It does not absolve my ex husband's actions, but it shouldn't negate my own faults, either.

I’m a foreigner living in China, my city has been on lockdown for 2 weeks now with at least one week until we go back to work. Barely anything is open, so there’s nothing to do besides grocery shopping right now. 

I live right by a highway and there’s been such little traffic these past few weeks it’s crazy, there used to be hour long traffic jams during peak times.

*New Virus Appears*

*WHO:* We should keep an eye on it but the likelihood of it spreading to other countries is low.

comment: The amount of misinformation and intentional misleading facts about face masks is absurd. There are headlines from major organizations painting face masks as literally useless as protection from illness. That is so far from true, that it's actually making conspiracy theories about the government intentionally trying to get the people sick (i.e. antivaxx bullshit) seem plausible. All medical face masks provide some form of protection. 100% fact. The difference is how effective they are, with generic surgical masks providing the least, while ones like the popular N95 masks providing much better protection. When headlines and opinion state that face masks are unhelpful or useless, they are literally trying to mislead you. What they are often actually saying is that compared to normal proper hygiene, it is not as effective. That is also (generally) a fact. That does not however mean that face masks are an ineffective measure to protect yourself, assuming you are using it correctly and effectively (e.g. not touching the main part of the mask, using it only for a short period of time, your nose/mouth does not make contact with the mask, etc). There are people even claiming that the idea of bacteria/viruses infecting people through their eyes is impossible... you know, like pink eye doesn't exist.

comment:
Can everyone please shut up, and stop moaning about "feminism that" or "toxic masculinity this" for just two seconds? I've seen a lot of really disgusting comments here that generalize both genders way too much. The reality is that all human beings, both men AND women, have the capacity to do both good and evil. There are just as many pros and cons to encouraging boys to be masculine as there are pros and cons to women wanting to empower themselves through feminism. But none of that shit should even really matter at the end of the day. If you want to figure out whether or not someone is a saint or a devil, then you need to do something other than argue with strangers over the internet over flimsy ideologies. Look at a person's actions. That's where you will find the answer.

If that sounded really preachy, I'm sorry. But I have watched people argue over this inane bullshit for years now, and in these past few years it's gotten to the point where I and many others just can't take it anymore.

comment:
I went through something very similar to Depp. My first love was someone i thought i could spend my life with. But whenever things became tough and tensions were high, she became someone who was physically and verbally abusive. The further i tried to create space, the more vindictive she became. I once had to lock myself in my truck after a failed talk in an attempt to set in motion  a peaceful breakup. On the outside she SCREAMED the most vile things you could tell someone whom you knew their every weakness, their vulnerabilities, their fears. For me it was to tell me my father who commited suicide when i was 15 "never loved me". That i'd "be a failure like him". As she raged smashing the outside of my car with her fists and eventually a shoe and other objects.  I sat paralyzed in my seat. In the attemt to keep stockholm out of my head, i was immobilized by the fear of hurting her(emotionally) while wanting so bad to flea from the hurt that i was undergoing. To resist giving her everything she wanted just to make it all go away so that she could go back to loving me, to the good times.

Eventually the screaming caught the attention of a witnes. Someone who saw this in the parking lot and who contacted the police. It wasn't till after talking to a female officer that day that i realized i had never even thought of a man being a victim of abuse. This is what you're told as a man: you never hit a woman, i despise violence, check; you remain and take it like a man, okay i do nothing, its probably my fault even when its not, check... I didn't press charges because i loved that person, and i knew she could change if she truely tried. Update, she did for the most part. At least from what i can tell as somewhat distant friends who hardly ever talk. But ive heard good things from others so I'll give her the full benifit of the doubt.

But im saying this all in an effort to let people know that abuse occurs both ways. That from someone who's been on the end of conniving vindictiveness of what a broken person is capable of..  You shouldn't always just jump to believing someone because they're of a certain sex or because you have an affiliation to the team. Men have privilege, we certainly do. There are also privileges which women recieve. The system favors a woman in these instances, and as a society we need to be vigilant in ensuring that it's not being abused and used as a tool to hurt others. In somecases the men whom they perceive have wronged and hurt them. I've seen this in divorces and child custody of close guy friends more than once over the years. Its important to support victims, but its also and somewhay equally important to establish the truth before inadvertently creating another victim via public humiliation, exile, the figurative execution of ones personhood. If you're one of those people who jumps on the hype train, i beg you to reconsider your ways. The process at which you come to a conclusion could seriously hurt other people.

This evidence shows that it's very likely that his wife was the abuser. Though a court case should be fully heard. Whatever happens and whomever is at fault, people should have a chance to redeem themselves. To put forth an effort for change before being relegated to banishment from the public sphere. So no matter what happens i look forward to seeing Johnny in the next Grindelwald film. The Potter stories have served as an escape for me over the years and i think he has every right to be in those films. If you disagree, start back at the top, you might have missed something.

comment:
Regarding the first story:
As a consumer of media with personal preferences for Depp, I find these “he said she said” arguments very annoying. Is it so hard to have this battle in court, without the media being present? I would argue that during such a trial both parties would present all the evidence against one another and the judge could make a well founded decision. After the judgment the media can report on a full story with every piece of evidence. 
These elongated “he said she said” arguments in public make me feel used as a consumer. With the clicks on articles, with the shares of articles and the tweets about a topic, the consumers shape an argument between two people and also their lives, creating and destroying career opportunities. And during all of that we cannot be sure that either side has presented all their evidence because it was not convenient at the time to shape the public opinion. 
If you want to have a fair trial in my humble opinion it is vital to keep the media out.

comment:
Personally, I think the government is overreacting, considering previous CDC and WHO statements. The more cynical part of me thinks this probably is somewhat a retaliation for China's grounding of Boeing jets and/or getting more bargaining chips for the next round of trade talk. Is it good for publici health here to impose a travel ban? Of course it is. Does the current situation warrant such a drastic measure? Probably not. 
I did some digging, and it appears that reasons why the amount of infected is way more than SARS in 2002 are a combination of factors:
a. the 2019-nCoV has a relatively longer incubation period (14 days) comparing to SARS (7 days), during which the virus can spread. A lot of people may spread it before the symptoms profess themselves.
b. the 2019-nCoV occurred during the Chinese New Year, when (according to some) as much as half of Chinese population would be traveling back and forth within China, increasing the probability of spreading the virus.
c. modes of transportation have significantly improved from 2003, making it easier for the virus to spread.
That being said, I heard there were also major government oversight from the officials in Wuhan. Word is the entire leadership in Wuhan was relieved of duty. 
As of now, there are 11 confirmed cases in the US. Considering the virus is now on everybody's radar, I'm optimistic that this wouldn't be an overwhelming problem for us to panic about, but still, BE CAUTIOUS!

comment:
Not gonna lie, tad bit disappointed with the coverage of the Heard/Depp situation. I understand needing to remain impartial, but there were so many more damning clips in that audio. Could've shaved down the sponsor or TIA if time was an issue.

In the audio, she admits to throwing all kinds of objects at him. Berates him nigh on constantly, calling him a "baby" and a "coward" for leaving when she starts becoming violent. Throws homophobic insults at him and his friend. Compares herself to a wild, uncontrollable animal being poked with a stick, which is a common comparison abusers like to make to blame their anger on their victim. Forced a bloody Xanax on the man. The audio is a goldmine of confessions from Heard, and all of those individual confessions needed to be showcased. There are people out there unwilling to listen to the audio at all, hence why it's so important to spread this.

It's important too, because the mainstream media seem to be shying the eff away from the story. So I thought, and was hoping, that you guys would go *all in* on it. No need for Philly D to take sides, even. Impartiality still in tact. Let Amber Heard speak for herself, because that content was entirely damning, and people needed to hear more of it.

If anyone happens to read my comment and hasn't yet listened to the audio in full, please go and do that. It's disturbing to listen to, but it paints a pretty clear picture of what went down, and the dynamics of their relationship. Amber Heard is awful, and I hope one day adequate justice is served.

comment:
The Johnny depp case is something that I’ve sat back on for awhile. There wasn’t enough evidence or information to know who was actually in the wrong, but you still saw people jumping to one side of the other usually to defend the person they already liked more. I still however don’t think there’s enough evidence to soundly make a call on what actually happened on this relationship. Clearly we know now that she was violent towards him, but we don’t really know how much of that was aggravated or if it was totally on her. 

As someone who’s been in an intense abusive situation, I know that you can only take so much. I eventually fought back, and when I did my abuser used that against me and had the police on his side. It would be great to have more audio and evidence released, to see if there’s any discussion about him starting physical fights. But from the clip we do have it definitely seems odd for them to discuss her physical violence without her mentioning his aggressions if there were any. So again for now I can’t “cancel” either of them or take a side here. I just think its sad that a personal relationship got so out of hand and is having to be released to the public like this. 

If someone is being mentally or physically abusive to you in a relationship you should take every step to get out as soon as possible no matter what. They’re unlikely to change, and you’re worth more than that.

comment:
My sister has been physically and mentally abusing her husband for many years.  Despite many times going to authorities, a history of unstableness and violence on her part, and corroborating evidence from people including their children (two of them legal adults) the courts have refused to do anything.  Until, of course, she complained that *he* was being abusive.  At that point, with her statements being the only evidence, *he* was kicked out of the house.


We have a dangerous double standard in this country.  There are many places where women get the short end of the stick, for sure, but when it comes to things like domestic abuse, custody, child support, etc, women are often given preferential treatment or just given more credibility than men. 



Domestic abuse is never ok, and it is perpetrated by both men and women.

comment:
As a male and an abuse survivor, the worst part is how everything Amber said I could predict. 


She said every argument made against me, especially everytime i broke down and cried from being beaten or emotionally abused.  

On the receiving end you never know what the hell they expect as a response to their actions but you sure as hell know that they will keep pushing you until they get it or grow bored / calm down. 


It's honestly the scariest time of my life. Frequently I would be reminded (after the same as what amber herd said or similar) of how she would dream of stabbing me or killing me in my sleep. 


I never want anybody to suffer that again. It has been years since but i had an awful flashback the other day when me and my new partner (who treats me insanely well who i am so glad for) were unsure as to where to eat, but with the ex who abused me it was a matter of if i didn't know or didn't decide before her then she would beat the shit out of me for indecisiveness.  This also extended to wanting something she didn't want and how i am the asshole who deserves to be beaten for not knowing what she wants. 


30mins later I need to stop crying to collect the delivery, and if i don't feel like eating then you know what happens next. 


Arguably the worst 5-6 years of my life. it broke me. Not only on the experience, but as a male for how you have absolutely nobody to talk to and the feeling that nobody will understand.

comment:
I am sorry if you ADMIT to STARTING a physical altercation YOU ARE NOT THE VICTIM. IF YOUR VICTIM the person you started the altercation upon injures you more than you injured them, YOU ARE NOT THE VICTIM. You picked a fight and lost. If someone is psychologically abusing you or abusing you with words and you leave, you remain the victim, if your psychological abuse makes you physically abusive you are no longer the victim, Physical Violence is not a proper response to verbal or psychological misdoings.

If you are being abused in any way regardless of what you and the person abusing you have between your legs, Get out, Get Help, there are fewer resources for men to get help in these cases but they do exist. Do not Suffer abuse, if someone is abusing you, they do not love you and you can not expect for them to change to love you, you may love them but it WILL be better for you to never see them, or hear from them ever again.


I know that the first bit of this comment sounds kind of Victim blaming, saying that a victim of one type of abuse lashing out physically then is no longer the victim, but the point is that you can HAVE been the victim of verbal or psychological abuse, but that is not an excuse for physical abuse in return. If you abuse your abuser you give them power, and it stops mattering who started it how, and starts mattering who did the most damage, and that is not what we should be seeking to find when dealing with abuse what we should be seeking to find is who is the abuser and preventing them from abusing their victim.

comment:
Something people forget about the Depp/Heard issue is the age/power imbalance: while I personally have completely no idea what has gone down re the violence in their relationship, it cannot be denied that he was ALWAYS older, richer and more powerful than Amber, down to the fact that she is a woman and he is a man, and yes, men are usually going to be physically stronger than women. That is fact.

The problem with mutual relationship violence/in a marriage, is that yes, I think women DO abuse men probably nearly amount as the reverse, however when a man hits back it can do FAR more damage than a woman hitting a man can, in general broad strokes. Of course I am generalizing, and NO violence towards ANYONE is ok, but the odds are stacked against Depp and while again, I honestly don't know who did what, I still think it is marginally more likely that Depp hurt Amber more, in the short and long term--but I am open to this being disproven. 

Amber was a 23, 24 year old rising star.
Johnny was a super-famous established, respected actor. 

There was always a power imbalance in their relationship. 

My opinion? I think they are both immoral, unstable individuals that should never have begun a relationship and it's probably both of them in the wrong here.

comment: I know almost nothing about the Johnny Depp/ Amber Heard case, so I have no opinion about who is "more" right. However, as a woman who withstood significant emotional abuse for years, during which time I slapped my boyfriend three times and kicked him once, I sympathise with the idea that it's not a black and white situation. It is still something I would take back in a second, and I consider it the worst thing(s) I have ever done. However, it was definitely retaliatory. After 4 hours of an adult man literally screaming at you, trying to rip you apart and hurt you as much as possible, sometimes in a very physically threatening way, it can feel absolutely as if you are fighting for your life and you need to do whatever you can to fight back. I cannot stress enough how scary it is. It feels like there is just one hair trigger between him screaming how horrible you are and him deciding he needs to physically attack you. I was physically hurt a few times during this relationship, and once it has happened the emotional trigger is there and you are constantly terrified it will happen again. Hence the feeling of fighting "back" for your life. I do not in any way condone or legitimize these actions, and like I said I am extremely ashamed of them. I have been led to believe from research while trying to heal and from a therapist who used to be a police officer that woman very often are fighting BACK, and are not as often the initial aggressors. Again, often is not always and any physical assault is always wrong, but it is NOT a situation we can see clearly from the outside and judge with any accuracy.

comment:
Hey Phil, I’ve listened to the whole audio, and as a social worker who’s worked with both DV victims and perpetrators, I’m still not sure but I’m erring towards supporting Amber. I get the urge to want to protect our heroes, I loved Johnny Depp for so long but having worked in domestic and family violence for a long time, I feel he is clearly gas lighting her and setting her up. We need to remember that Amber is only in her 20s here, this is one of her first real relationships with someone she clearly adored, Johnny is in his 50s and has age, experience and Xanax on his side. Note that he repeatedly asks her to send him the tapes since they’re being recorded on her phone. When he talks about her violence he names exactly what it is and what happened: YOU threw cans at me in Australia, YOU threw pots and pans, YOU punched me last night, but then sometimes he’s super vague about random acts of violence like when he says “if you had spoken to me nicely it wouldn’t have gotten physical those times”. It’s likely that during those times he’s actually describing his own violence, not hers, he just knows well enough not to record himself admitting to something, whereas she is too gullible and naive.

When women are dragged into a DV relationship, they often do become violent themselves, whether it is in self defence or whether it is in an effort to just get the beating they know is coming over with. There is a lot of documented research about this phenomenon. Many women describe an intuitive feeling where they know an outburst is going to happen and so they subconsciously bring that about through their own actions in an effort to control their situation.

I think we need to be careful before taking a position here. He’s smart enough to play the game, she thinks she’s involved in a meaningful conversation to repair their relationship. That’s why she takes responsibility for her behaviour and he controls his delivery and hides his actions with vagueness. Note that he says she attacks him when he means she criticised him verbally and he doesn’t correct her when she points that out. Also when he calls her losing her marbles when he just means she’s stressing out about something. He overplays what she’s done and underplays his actions. This is pretty classic abusive behaviour and gaslighting.

I ask not because I do or don't believe either of them as not all evidence has come out (as clearly has been shown), but because her lawyers pushed back suggesting that just because Depp was hit doesn't mean that she isn't also a victim. Of course, we don't know at what time during this relationship this occured (although it does not appear to be towards the beginning based on the language used) and that may impact the facts in the tape since the facts could have changed later on.  Whatever the case, I do hope the truth becomes known, not because I want to put my nose where it doesn't belong (especially since it's already a somewhat public matter), but because I do not want anyone else to be further hurt physically, mentally or yes, even in terms of ones career.
